1 STATE OF OKLAHOMA
2 2nd Session of the 60th Legislature (2026)
3 SUBCOMMITTEE RECOMMENDATION
FOR
4 HOUSE BILL NO. 3585 By: Harris
5
6
7
8 SUBCOMMITTEE RECOMMENDATION
9 An Act relating to court reporters; amending 20 O.S.
2021, Section 106.4, as amended by Section 1, Chapter
10 100, O.S.L. 2023 (20 O.S. Supp. 2025, Section 106.4),
which relates to duties of court reporters; expanding
11 means by which a court reporter can record; removing
prohibition on certification of persons who rely
12 exclusively upon a steno-mask; clarifying use of
proceedings electronically recorded when no court
13 reporter is available; amending 20 O.S. 2021, Section
106.9, as last amended by Section 1, Chapter 263,
14 O.S.L. 2023 (20 O.S. Supp. 2025, Section 106.9),
which relates to court reporter compensation; adding
15 certifications to additional compensation payments;
removing certain continuing education requirement;
16 authorizing Supreme Court to direct continuing
education requirements; suspending additional
17 compensation payment if there is a lapse in
certification; amending 20 O.S. 2021, Section 1503,
18 which relates to examination of court reporters;
changing methods for which a certification can be
19 issued; and declaring an emergency.
20
21
22 BE IT ENACTED BY THE PEOPLE OF THE STATE OF OKLAHOMA:
23
24
Req. No. 16432 Page 1

1 SECTION 1. AMENDATORY 20 O.S. 2021, Section 106.4, as
2 amended by Section 1, Chapter 100, O.S.L. 2023 (20 O.S. Supp. 2025,
3 Section 106.4), is amended to read as follows:
4 Section 106.4. A. 1. The court reporter shall make a full
5 reporting by means of stenographic hand, steno-mask stenomask or,
6 stenographic machine notes, or any other method of reporting
7 authorized by the Supreme Court, or a combination thereof, of all
8 proceedings, including the statements of counsel and the court and
9 the evidence, in trials and other judicial proceedings to which the
10 court reporter is assigned by the appointing judge unless excused by
11 the judge who is trying the case with the consent of the parties to
12 the action. Nothing herein contained shall be construed to
13 authorize the certification of persons as certified shorthand
14 reporters who rely exclusively upon the steno-mask for reporting
15 judicial proceedings, except as provided by law. A refusal of the
16 court to permit or to require any statement to be taken down by the
17 court reporter or transcribed after being taken down, upon the same
18 being shown by affidavit or other direct and competent evidence, to
19 the Supreme Court, or other appellate court, shall constitute a
20 denial of due process of law. The court reporter may use an
21 electronic instrument as a supplementary device.
22 2. In any trial, hearing, or proceedings, if no court reporter
23 is available to the assigned judge either in person or remotely:
24
Req. No. 16432 Page 2

1 a. the judge before whom the matter is being heard may
2 order the proceedings electronically recorded and a
3 trial, hearing, or proceedings may proceed without the
4 necessity of a court reporter being present. Provided
5 that if an official transcript is ordered then it
6 shall be prepared by the official court reporter Any
7 party may order a transcript from the proceedings
8 electronically recorded; provided that, only
9 transcripts prepared by an official court reporter may
10 be used in any subsequent trial, hearing, proceeding,
11 or appeal, or
12 b. with approval of the judge, the parties may stipulate
13 to the use of a freelance reporter and share the cost.
14 If ordered, the transcript shall be prepared by the
15 approved reporter and shall be considered the official
16 transcript for all purposes.
17 B. 1. Upon request of either party in a civil or criminal
18 case, the reporter shall transcribe the proceedings in a trial or
19 other judicial proceeding, or so much thereof as may be requested by
20 the party, certify to the correctness of the transcript, and deliver
21 the same in accordance with the rules of the Supreme Court. The fee
22 for an original transcript shall be set by the Supreme Court. Two
23 copies of the original transcript shall be furnished without
24 additional charge. Each page shall be at least twenty-five lines to
Req. No. 16432 Page 3

1 the page and typed no fewer than nine characters to the typed inch.
2 Each page shall be no more than double spaced and the margin on the
3 left side of the page shall be no more than one and one-half (1 1/2)
4 inches and the margin on the right side of the page shall be no more
5 than one-half (1/2) inch from the edge of the paper. The format for
6 all transcripts shall be prescribed by the Supreme Court. The fees
7 for making the transcript shall be paid in the first instance by the
8 party requesting the transcript and shall be taxed as costs in the
9 suit.
10 2. When the judge on his or her own motion orders a transcript
11 of the reporter's notes, the judge may direct the payment of charges
12 and the taxation of the charges as costs in such manner as the court
13 deems appropriate. In a criminal action, if the defendant shall
14 present to the judge an affidavit that the defendant intends in good
15 faith to take an appeal in the case and that a transcript of the
16 reporter's notes is necessary to enable the defendant to prosecute
17 the appeal, and that he or she has not the means to pay for the
18 transcript, the court, upon finding that there is reasonable basis
19 for the averment, shall order the transcript made at the expense of
20 the district court fund. The format preparation, delivery and
21 filing of transcripts to be used in civil and criminal appeals may
22 be regulated by the Supreme Court.
23
24
Req. No. 16432 Page 4

1 C. The court reporter shall file his or her records of the
2 evidence and the proceedings taken in any case with the clerk of the
3 court in which the case was tried.
4 D. To the extent that it does not substantially interfere with
5 the court reporter's other official duties, the judge by whom a
6 reporter is employed or to whom he or she is assigned may assign a
7 reporter to secretarial or clerical duties arising out of official
8 court operations.
9 SECTION 2. AMENDATORY 20 O.S. 2021, Section 106.9, as
10 last amended by Section 1, Chapter 263, O.S.L. 2023 (20 O.S. Supp.
11 2025, Section 106.9), is amended to read as follows:
12 Section 106.9. A. Each court reporter regularly engaged by the
13 district court, the Workers' Compensation Court of Existing Claims,
14 or the Corporation Commission shall be paid a salary pursuant to the
15 salary schedule established by the annual appropriation for the
16 district courts and Corporation Commission and in accordance with
17 the job description for the position to which appointed. For fiscal
18 year 2023 and each fiscal year thereafter, each court reporter shall
19 receive an annual salary of Fifty-three Thousand Dollars
20 ($53,000.00).
21 B. In addition to their base salaries, official court reporters
22 who are certified or licensed shorthand reporters and those acting
23 shorthand reporters pursuant to paragraph 3 of Section 106.3B of
24 this title shall be paid annually the sum of Four Hundred Dollars
Req. No. 16432 Page 5

1 ($40 0.00) for each year of service to the district court, the
2 Workers' Compensation Court, the Workers' Compensation Court of
3 Existing Claims and the Corporation Commission, with a maximum of
4 twenty (20) years of service only to be used for the purpose of
5 longevity, not to exceed Eight Thousand Dollars ($8,000.00) per
6 year, payable monthly. For the purpose of payment for longevity,
7 "years of service" is defined as all years served as a certified or
8 licensed court reporter in the district court, the Workers'
9 Compensation Court, the Workers' Compensation Court of Existing
10 Claims and the Corporation Commission after June 30, 1978.
11 Longevity payments shall be made on July 1 of each year following
12 completion of the first year of service as defined herein.
13 C. In addition to their base salaries, official court reporters
14 eligible for longevity payments pursuant to subsection B of this
15 section shall be paid an annual equipment allowance of Three
16 Thousand Dollars ($3,000.00). Payments for such allowance shall be
17 made on July 1 of each year following completion of the first year
18 of service as defined in subsection B of this section.
19 D. In addition to their base salaries, official court reporters
20 who are certified shorthand reporters shall be paid the following:
21 1. The sum of Two Thousand Dollars ($2,000.00) per year,
22 payable monthly, to any official court reporter who is a holds one
23 or more of the following certifications:
24
Req. No. 16432 Page 6

1 a. Registered Professional Reporter (RPR), as recognized
2 by the State Board of Examiners of Certified Shorthand
3 Reporters. To qualify as a RPR, an official court
4 reporter shall have a National Court Reporters
5 Association,
6 b. Certified Verbatim Reporter, as recognized by the
7 National Verbatim Reporters Association,
8 c. Certified Verbatim Reporter – Stenotype (CVR-S), as
9 recognized by the National Verbatim Reporters
10 Association, or
11 d. other certifications authorized by the Supreme Court
12 that demonstrate a proficiency level in reporting
13 testimony and proceedings of a speed of not less than
14 two hundred twenty-five (225) words per minute in
15 taking a question-and-answer-type dictation, two
16 hundred (200) words per minute in taking a jury
17 charge, and one hundred eighty (180) words per minute
18 in taking literary material,. In addition, the
19 individual shall pass a the Oklahoma Written Knowledge
20 Test with a score of at least seventy percent (70%),
21 all as determined by an examination recognized by the
22 Board, and shall complete thirty (30) hours of
23 continuing education per three-year cycle commencing
24
